  "why": "The paper's primary objective is to create a data augmentation technique that improves the robustness of DNNs, rather than to diagnose the root causes of model failures. The proposed method, SENSEI, uses a genetic search to find input variants that maximize the model's loss function. These 'failure-inducing' or 'most lossy' variants are then immediately used to augment the training data to make the model more robust. The evaluation focuses exclusively on quantifying the improvement in 'robust accuracy' after applying this augmentation technique. The paper reports the aggregate success of the method but does not provide any analysis of the generated failure cases themselves. There is no discussion linking the discovered failures to underlying model vulnerabilities (like dataset bias or reliance on non-robust features), nor is there an analysis of statistical failure patterns (e.g., which classes are more susceptible) or model internals (e.g., neuron activation patterns). The generated failures are a means to an end (robust training), not objects of diagnostic study.",
